.TH "HTMLDIALOGELEMENT" "3JS" "January 26, 2026" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
HTMLDialogElement \- HTMLDialogElement
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]HTMLDialogElement\f[B]\f[R] interface provides methods to
manipulate \f[CR]<dialog>\f[R] elements.
It inherits properties and methods from the \f[CR]HTMLElement\f[R]
interface.
.SH INSTANCE PROPERTIES
\f[I]Also inherits properties from its parent interface,
\f[CI]HTMLElement\f[I].\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]HTMLDialogElement.closedBy\f[R]
A string that sets or returns the \f[CR]closedby\f[R] HTML attribute,
indicating the types of user actions that can be used to close the
dialog.
.TP
\f[B]HTMLDialogElement.open\f[R]
A boolean value reflecting the \f[CR]open\f[R] HTML attribute,
indicating whether the dialog is available for interaction.
.TP
\f[B]HTMLDialogElement.returnValue\f[R]
A string that sets or returns the return value for the dialog.
.SH INSTANCE METHODS
\f[I]Also inherits methods from its parent interface,
\f[CI]HTMLElement\f[I].\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]HTMLDialogElement.close()\f[R]
Closes the dialog.
An optional string may be passed as an argument, updating the
\f[CR]returnValue\f[R] of the dialog.
.TP
\f[B]HTMLDialogElement.requestClose()\f[R]
Requests to close the dialog.
An optional string may be passed as an argument, updating the
\f[CR]returnValue\f[R] of the dialog.
.TP
\f[B]HTMLDialogElement.show()\f[R]
Displays the dialog modelessly, i.e., still allowing interaction with
content outside of the dialog.
.TP
\f[B]HTMLDialogElement.showModal()\f[R]
Displays the dialog as a modal, over the top of any other dialogs that
might be present.
Everything outside the dialog is \f[CR]inert\f[R] with interactions
outside the dialog being blocked.
.SH EVENTS
\f[I]Also inherits events from its parent interface,
\f[CI]HTMLElement\f[I].\f[R]
.PP
Listen to these events using \f[CR]addEventListener()\f[R] or by
assigning an event listener to the \f[CR]oneventname\f[R] property of
this interface.
.TP
\f[B]cancel\f[R]
Fired when the dialog is requested to close, whether with the escape
key, or via the \f[CR]requestClose()\f[R] method.
If the event is canceled (via \f[CR]Event.preventDefault()\f[R]), the
dialog will remain open.
If not canceled, the dialog will close and the \f[CR]close\f[R] event
will be fired.
.TP
\f[B]close\f[R]
Fired when the dialog is closed.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Open / close a modal dialog
The following example shows a button that, when clicked, uses the
\f[CR]showModal()\f[R] function to open a modal dialog containing a
form.
.PP
While open, everything other than the modal dialog\(cqs contents is
inert.
You can click the \f[I]Close\f[R] button to close the dialog (via the
\f[CR]close()\f[R] function), or submit the form via the
\f[I]Confirm\f[R] button.
.PP
The example demonstrates:
.IP "1." 3
Closing a form with the \f[CR]close()\f[R] function
.IP "2." 3
Closing a form on form submit and setting the dialog
\f[CR]returnValue\f[R]
.IP "3." 3
Closing a form with the Esc key
.IP "4." 3
\(lqstate change\(rq events that can be fired on the dialog:
\f[CR]cancel\f[R] and \f[CR]close\f[R], and the inherited events
\f[CR]beforetoggle\f[R], and \f[CR]toggle\f[R].
.SS HTML
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]dialog\f[R] id=\(dqdialog\(dq>
  <\f[B]button\f[R] id=\(dqclose\(dq type=\(dqbutton\(dq>Close</\f[B]button\f[R]>
  <\f[B]form\f[R] method=\(dqdialog\(dq id=\(dqform\(dq>
    <\f[B]p\f[R]>
      <\f[B]label\f[R] for=\(dqfav\-animal\(dq>Favorite animal:</\f[B]label\f[R]>
      <\f[B]select\f[R] id=\(dqfav\-animal\(dq name=\(dqfavAnimal\(dq required>
        <\f[B]option\f[R]></\f[B]option\f[R]>
        <\f[B]option\f[R]>Brine shrimp</\f[B]option\f[R]>
        <\f[B]option\f[R]>Red panda</\f[B]option\f[R]>
        <\f[B]option\f[R]>Spider monkey</\f[B]option\f[R]>
      </\f[B]select\f[R]>
    </\f[B]p\f[R]>
    <\f[B]div\f[R]>
      <\f[B]button\f[R] id=\(dqsubmit\(dq type=\(dqsubmit\(dq>Confirm</\f[B]button\f[R]>
    </\f[B]div\f[R]>
  </\f[B]form\f[R]>
</\f[B]dialog\f[R]>

<\f[B]button\f[R] id=\(dqopen\(dq>Open dialog</\f[B]button\f[R]>
.EE
.SS JavaScript
.SS Open the dialog
The code first gets objects for the \f[CR]<dialog>\f[R] element, the
\f[CR]<button>\f[R] elements, and the \f[CR]<select>\f[R] element.
It then adds a listener to call the
\f[CR]HTMLDialogElement.showModal()\f[R] function when the \f[I]Open
Dialog\f[R] button is clicked.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] dialog = document.getElementById(\(dqdialog\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] openButton = document.getElementById(\(dqopen\(dq);

\f[I]// Open button opens a modal dialog\f[R]
openButton.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  log(\(gadialog: showModal()\(ga);
  dialog.showModal();
});
.EE
.SS Close the dialog when the \f[I]Close\f[R] button is clicked
Next we add a listener to the \f[I]Close\f[R] button \f[CR]click\f[R]
event.
The handler set the \f[CR]returnValue\f[R] and calls the
\f[CR]close()\f[R] function to close the dialog.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Close button closes the dialog box\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] closeButton = document.getElementById(\(dqclose\(dq);
closeButton.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  dialog.returnValue = \(dq\(dq; \f[I]// Reset return value\f[R]
  log(\(gadialog: close()\(ga);
  dialog.close();
  \f[I]// Alternatively, we could use dialog.requestClose(\(dq\(dq); with an empty return value.\f[R]
});
.EE
.SS Close the dialog when \f[I]Confirm\f[R] button is clicked via form submission
Next we add a listener to the \f[CR]<form>\f[R] \f[CR]submit\f[R] event.
The form is submitted when the required \f[CR]<select>\f[R] element has
a value and the \f[I]Confirm\f[R] button is clicked.
If the \f[CR]<select>\f[R] element does not have a value the form will
not submit and the dialog will remain open.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Confirm button closes dialog if there is a selection.\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] form = document.getElementById(\(dqform\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] selectElement = document.getElementById(\(dqfav\-animal\(dq);
form.addEventListener(\(dqsubmit\(dq, () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  log(\(gaform: submit\(ga);
  \f[I]// Set the return value to the selected option value\f[R]
  dialog.returnValue = selectElement.value;
  \f[I]// We don\(aqt need to close the dialog here\f[R]
  \f[I]// submitting the form with method=\(dqdialog\(dq will do that automatically.\f[R]
  \f[I]// dialog.close();\f[R]
});
.EE
.SS Get the \f[CR]returnValue\f[R] on \f[CR]close\f[R]
Calling \f[CR]close()\f[R] (or successfully submitting a form with
\f[CR]method=\(dqdialog\(dq\f[R]\(lq) fires the \f[CR]close\f[R] event,
which we implement below by logging the return value of the dialog.
.IP
.EX
dialog.addEventListener(\(dqclose\(dq, (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  log(\(gaclose_event: (dialog.returnValue: \(dq${dialog.returnValue}\(dq)\(ga);
});
.EE
.SS \f[CR]cancel\f[R] event
The \f[CR]cancel\f[R] event is fired when \(lqplatform specific
methods\(rq are used to close the dialog, such as the Esc key.
It is also fired when the \f[CR]requestClose()\f[R] method is called.
The event is \(lqcancelable\(rq which means that we could use it to
prevent the dialog from closing.
Here we just treat the cancel as a \(lqclose\(rq operation, and reset
the \f[CR]returnValue\f[R] to \f[CR]\(dq\(dq\f[R] to clear any value
that may have been set.
.IP
.EX
dialog.addEventListener(\(dqcancel\(dq, (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  log(\(gacancel_event: (dialog.returnValue: \(dq${dialog.returnValue}\(dq)\(ga);
  dialog.returnValue = \(dq\(dq; \f[I]// Reset value\f[R]
});
.EE
.SS \f[CR]toggle\f[R] event
The \f[CR]toggle\f[R] event (inherited from \f[CR]HTMLElement\f[R]) is
fired just after a dialog has opened or closed (but before the
\f[CR]close\f[R] event).
.PP
Here we add a listener to log when the dialog opens and closes.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] The \f[CR]toggle\f[R] and \f[CR]beforetoggle\f[R] events
may not be fired at dialog elements on all browsers.
On these browser versions you can instead check the \f[CR]open\f[R]
property after attempting to open/close the dialog.
.RE
.IP
.EX
dialog.addEventListener(\(dqtoggle\(dq, (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  log(\(gatoggle event: newState: ${event.newState}\(ga);
});
.EE
.SS \f[CR]beforetoggle\f[R] event
The \f[CR]beforetoggle\f[R] event (inherited from
\f[CR]HTMLElement\f[R]) is a cancellable event that is fired just before
a dialog is opened or closed.
If needed, this can be used to prevent a dialog from showing, or to
perform actions on other elements that are affected by the dialog
open/close state, such as adding classes on them to trigger animations.
.PP
In this case we just log the old and new state.
.IP
.EX
dialog.addEventListener(\(dqbeforetoggle\(dq, (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  log(
    \(gabeforetoggle event: oldState: ${event.oldState}, newState: ${event.newState}\(ga,
  );

  \f[I]// Call event.preventDefault() to prevent a dialog opening\f[R]
  \f[I]/*\f[R]
\f[I]    if (shouldCancel()) {\f[R]
\f[I]        event.preventDefault();\f[R]
\f[I]    }\f[R]
\f[I]  */\f[R]
});
.EE
.SS Result
Try out the example below.
Note that both \f[CR]Confirm\f[R] and \f[CR]Close\f[R] buttons result in
the \f[CR]close\f[R] event being fired, and that the result should
reflect the selected dialog option.
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
HTML \f[CR]<dialog>\f[R] element
